There will be a few general actions at the bottom of each post like
>>ATTACK
>>SKILLS
>>INTERACT
>>INVENTORY
>>PARTY
or other actions if you specify. No dice rolls since that will confuse people that aren't into DnD, so I was thinking more along the lines of HarmonQuest where the mechanics are still similar, but I'll leave out numbers and chances so that success is entirely dependent on if you performed something that aligned with how the scene was supposed to act out or some out-of-the-box thinking that surprises me. An example would be if the party is in a dungeon, you would reply with

>>INTERACT
Have the rat rogue walk in the front to sense traps.

or

>>INVENTORY
Take out a lantern so we can see better.

Again, being specific is good, and I can manage a separate pastebin to keep track of items and skills each character has.

Anonymous Sat 27 Jan 2018 19:30:38 No.13710664 Report

>>13710290
Step one would be some punctuation and formatting.

>Think someone could he me out a bit as this is gonna be something different then what I'm used to.
Very awkward as one sentence, especially since you're combining a question and a statement, and lack any sort of punctuation between them. Don't be afraid of short, simple sentences; ideas can be communicated across sentences. Roll with something like:
"Think someone could help me out? This is going to be different than I'm used to."
Or
"This is going to be different than I'm used to, could someone help me out?"

>What I need is well how do I write from the point of view of someone who's from 106 years in the past and now they get sent to the present

There is no reason to stumble over your words when writing unless you're writing dialogue, in which case you would notate something like
"What I need to do is--, well, how do I..."
>how do I write from the point of view of someone who's from 106 years in the past and now they get sent to the present
Missing comma plus confusing tense. Go for something like:
"how do I write from the point of view of someone from 106 years in the past who is sent to the present?"

I know this isn't really what you're looking for right now, but as it stands your work is almost unintelligible without several rereads. Do a little research on how grammar actually works, and slow the fuck down. I'm willing to bet you don't think in a chain if unpunctuated ideas that trip over themselves, and grammar is what will give you the tools to make it read the way it sounds in your head.

Anyway the answer to your question is you write it exactly the same as you would from anyone's perspective. All characters will be different in some ways regarding what they are or aren't aware of. In this case there will be a lot of that. Put yourself in her shoes. Call up a memory from the last time you were confused and faced with the utter foreign. Personal experience is a goldmine.

Know the basement in Degeneracy Pressure? That's from a family member's house whom lived in Cleveland. The late night radio shit and associated mood? From driving across country with my father in an old Chevy with a crappy radio. Anon's freezing up with fear when he turns to face Kali's ship? From countless nightmares and the first time I woke up to a snowplow, not knowing what the fuck it was. And the descriptions of meeting ayys in Degeneracy Pressure and other non /hmofa/ stories? Based on my interactions with the staff of a hole-in-the-wall Chinese restaurant I frequent whom I befriended despite the language barrier. Odds are you won't have an experience on hand that's exactly what you're looking for, but you can probably dig one up that operates along the same lines, and make use of it. For as crazy and complicated as our lives are, they only really make us feel a couple of very relatable ways. You may not know what it feels like to be a century out of time, but there's a good chance you've picked up what it feels like to be lonely, helpless, and confused. You likely don't know all those things from one event, but you've probably been all of them at least once. If you've lived enough, you might even know what it's like to have your world shattered. Maybe you were an only child for a long time, then suddenly became an older brother. Maybe you grew up awhile, and then someone told you you had autism. None of that is exactly what you're looking for, but it involves a stark change in perception and environment, and that's all being suddenly a century out of time is.
